Deep Learning Project: Street View Housing Number Digit Recognition¶

by: Nicolás Salazar Beltrán (nicolas-salbe.github.io)

Context¶

One of the most interesting tasks in deep learning is to recognize objects in natural scenes. The ability to process visual information using machine learning algorithms can be very useful as demonstrated in various applications.

The SVHN dataset contains over 600,000 labeled digits cropped from street-level photos. It is one of the most popular image recognition datasets. It has been used in neural networks created by Google to improve the map quality by automatically transcribing the address numbers from a patch of pixels. The transcribed number with a known street address helps pinpoint the location of the building it represents.

Objective¶

Our objective is to predict the number depicted inside the image by using Artificial or Fully Connected Feed Forward Neural Networks and Convolutional Neural Networks. We will go through various models of each and finally select the one that is giving us the best performance.

Dataset¶

Here, we will use a subset of the original data to save some computation time. The dataset is provided as a .h5 file. The basic preprocessing steps have been applied on the dataset.

Model Architecture¶

  • Write a function that returns a sequential model with the following architecture:
    • First hidden layer with 64 nodes and the relu activation and the input shape = (1024, )
    • Second hidden layer with 32 nodes and the relu activation
    • Output layer with activation as 'softmax' and number of nodes equal to the number of classes, i.e., 10
    • Compile the model with the loss equal to categorical_crossentropy, optimizer equal to Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), and metric equal to 'accuracy'. Do not fit the model here, just return the compiled model.
  • Call the nn_model_1 function and store the model in a new variable.
  • Print the summary of the model.
  • Fit on the train data with a validation split of 0.2, batch size = 128, verbose = 1, and epochs = 20. Store the model building history to use later for visualization.

Build and train an ANN model as per the above mentioned architecture.¶

In [ ]:
# Let's first import some additional classes
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [ ]:
def nn_model_1():
  model = Sequential()
  # 1st hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(64, input_shape=(1024,), activation='relu'))
  # 2nd hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
  # Output layer
  model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  # Model compilation
  model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])

  return model

Plot the Training and Validation Accuracies and write down your Observations.¶

In [ ]:
# Let's define a function for plotting the accuracies that we reuse later
def plot_accuracies(model_history):
  train_acc = model_history.history['accuracy']
  val_acc = model_history.history['val_accuracy']
  ax = plt.figure().gca()
  plt.plot(train_acc, 'bo-', label='Training')
  plt.plot(val_acc, 'r+-', label='Validation')
  plt.title('Accuracies vs. Epoch')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
  plt.xlabel('Epoch')
  plt.legend()

  plt.show()
In [ ]:
plot_accuracies(model_1_history)

Observations:___

  • The behavior of the training and the validation accuracies as the fitting progresses is very similar, indicating that the model is not overfitting.
  • After 20 epochs, both accuracies seem to be settling down around 0.67. In order to deal with this low performance we may increase the complexity of the ANN architecture. Increasing the number of epochs won't make much difference.
  • The architecture of model_1 is not very complex and therefore the fitting is not too computationally demanding.

Second Model Architecture¶

  • Write a function that returns a sequential model with the following architecture:
    • First hidden layer with 256 nodes and the relu activation and the input shape = (1024, )
    • Second hidden layer with 128 nodes and the relu activation
    • Add the Dropout layer with the rate equal to 0.2
    • Third hidden layer with 64 nodes and the relu activation
    • Fourth hidden layer with 64 nodes and the relu activation
    • Fifth hidden layer with 32 nodes and the relu activation
    • Add the BatchNormalization layer
    • Output layer with activation as 'softmax' and number of nodes equal to the number of classes, i.e., 10 -Compile the model with the loss equal to categorical_crossentropy, optimizer equal to Adam(learning_rate = 0.0005), and metric equal to 'accuracy'. Do not fit the model here, just return the compiled model.
  • Call the nn_model_2 function and store the model in a new variable.
  • Print the summary of the model.
  • Fit on the train data with a validation split of 0.2, batch size = 128, verbose = 1, and epochs = 30. Store the model building history to use later for visualization.

Build and train the new ANN model as per the above mentioned architecture¶

In [ ]:
# Let's first import some additional classes
from tensorflow.keras.layers import BatchNormalization
In [ ]:
def nn_model_2():
  model = Sequential()
  # 1st hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(256, input_shape=(1024,), activation='relu'))
  # 2nd hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  # droput layer
  model.add(Dropout(0.2))
  # 3rd hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
  # 4th hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
  # 5th hidden layer
  model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
  # batch normalization layer
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  # Output layer
  model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  # Model compilation
  model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0005), metrics=['accuracy'])

  return model

Observations:___

  • As in model_1, the training and validation accuracies go hand by hand in model_2. This suggests that the model is not overfitting.

  • The accuracies after 30 epochs seem to be settling down, which suggests that the fitting is close to converge.
  • model_2 is much more complex than model_1, which reflects on the increased computation time (the amount of parameters to train is more than 4 times that of model_1)

def print_prediction_metrics(actual, predicted):
  print('Classification Report: \n')
  print(classification_report(actual, predicted))
  cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
  plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d')
  plt.title('Confusion Matrix for Digit Predition')
  plt.ylabel('Actual digit')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted digit')
  plt.show()
In [ ]:
print_prediction_metrics(y_test, y_test_pred)

Final Observations:__

  • For digit detection precision and recall can be considered equally important. Therefore, the f1-score is a better metric for comparison. Overall, digit 3 is the most difficult digit to detect while digit 4 is the easiest.
  • Digit 3 is proportionally the least precisely detected digit, meaning that it leads to more false positives. Contrarily, digit 0 is the most precisely detected digit.
  • Digit 5 is proportionally the least recalled digit, meaning that it leads to more false negatives. Contrarily, digit 4 is the most recalled digit.
  • Digit 5 is more often misclassified as a 3. This could be due to the model having problems to detect some edges.
  • The overall detection accuracy 0.76 of X_test is practically the same as that of X_train, indicating that model_2 does generalize the fitting well.
  • From the support column it can be seen that samples for each class are pretty much balanced. Interestingly, digit 3 and digit 5 are the classes least represented. This could also explain their low detection scores in comparison with other digits as the model has less data to learn their corresponding parameters.
  • In general, model_2 has a fairly good accuracy suitable for applications that can tolerate wrong detections every now or then. For more demanding applications there's still room for improvement.

Model Architecture¶

  • Write a function that returns a sequential model with the following architecture:
    • First Convolutional layer with 16 filters and the kernel size of 3x3. Use the 'same' padding and provide the input shape = (32, 32, 1)
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Second Convolutional layer with 32 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding
    • Another LeakyRelu with the slope equal to 0.1
    • A max-pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    • Flatten the output from the previous layer
    • Add a dense layer with 32 nodes
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Add the final output layer with nodes equal to the number of classes, i.e., 10 and 'softmax' as the activation function
    • Compile the model with the loss equal to categorical_crossentropy, optimizer equal to Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), and metric equal to 'accuracy'. Do not fit the model here, just return the compiled model.

Build and train a CNN model as per the above mentioned architecture.¶

In [ ]:
# Let's first import some additional classes
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten, Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Activation, LeakyReLU
In [ ]:
def cnn_model_1():
  model = Sequential()
  # CNN: feature extraction
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", input_shape=(32,32,1)))  # using 2D convolution as images are in grayscale
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
  # Flatten
  model.add(Flatten())
  # ANN: classification
  model.add(Dense(32))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  # Output layer
  model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  # Model compilation
  model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])

  return model

Second Model Architecture¶

  • Write a function that returns a sequential model with the following architecture:
    • First Convolutional layer with 16 filters and the kernel size of 3x3. Use the 'same' padding and provide the input shape = (32, 32, 1)
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Second Convolutional layer with 32 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding
    • Add LeakyRelu with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Add a max-pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    • Add a BatchNormalization layer
    • Third Convolutional layer with 32 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Fourth Convolutional layer 64 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Add a max-pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    • Add a BatchNormalization layer
    • Flatten the output from the previous layer
    • Add a dense layer with 32 nodes
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Add a dropout layer with the rate equal to 0.5
    • Add the final output layer with nodes equal to the number of classes, i.e., 10 and 'softmax' as the activation function
    • Compile the model with the categorical_crossentropy loss, adam optimizers (learning_rate = 0.001), and metric equal to 'accuracy'. Do not fit the model here, just return the compiled model.
  • Call the function cnn_model_2 and store the model in a new variable.

Build and train the second CNN model as per the above mentioned architecture.¶

In [ ]:
def cnn_model_2():
  model = Sequential()
  # CNN: feature extraction
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", input_shape=(32,32,1)))  # using 2D convolution as images are in grayscale
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same"))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
  model.add(BatchNormalization())
  # Flatten
  model.add(Flatten())
  # ANN: classification
  model.add(Dense(32))
  model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
  model.add(Dropout(0.5))
  # Output layer
  model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

  # Model compilation
  model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])

  return model

Final Observations:_

  • Overall, digit 3 is the most difficult digit to detect. However, in comparison with model_2 the score gap between detecting a 3 and other digits is much smaller.
  • With a minimum f1-score of 0.89 (digit 3) cnn_model_2 does a very good job at detecting every digit in the dataset.
  • Digits 0, 4, and 7 can be thought to be equally as easy to detect.
  • Digit 1 is proportionally the least precisely detected digit, meaning that it leads to more false positives. Contrarily, digit 2 is the most precisely detected digit.
  • Digits 6 and 8 are proportionally the least recalled digit, meaning that they lead to more false negatives. Contrarily, digit 0 is the most recalled digit.
  • The overall detection accuracy 0.91 of X_test is a bit off from the training accuracy of X_train (0.95). This confirms that cnn_model_2 has some room for improvement to better generalize the fitting.
  • In general, cnn_model_2 has a good accuracy suitable for applications that can tolerate an overall 9% misclassification error.

Conclusions¶

  • For this digit detection task ANNs can achieve a discrete performance with no much architecture complexity. However, in order to achieve much better performance it is evident that CNNs are the way forward.
  • With half the parameters of model_2, cnn_model_2 achieved a much better accuracy. This indicates the convenience of feature extraction through convolution rather than mass learning a pattern with a fully connected ANN.
  • For images displaying more than one digit, the predicted digit seems to be the one in the center. This is something learnt by the models due to the labels themselves. Question remains whether this is a design choice.
  • Digits 3 and 5 are the most challenging to detect most likely because they are slightly under-represented in the dataset.
  • Some further improvements to deal with cnn_model_2 overfitting can include adding more regularization layers with Batch Normalization or Dropout or considering an optimizer with weight decay.
  • If more accuracy is required without adding more data then some options are to try other optimizers that may lead to more closely reaching the minimima of the loss function. Otherwise, an improvement of the architecture with transfer learning may also provide great results.
